{"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2023/06/22/press-freedom-is-stifled-in-guatemala-ahead-of-an-election", "__typename": "URL"}, "__typename": "Content", "id": "/content/918ahc3unf8kcurgs632ir9kf73e54st", "tegID": "918ahc3unf8kcurgs632ir9kf73e54st", "type": ["Article", "NewsArticle", "AnalysisNewsArticle"], "headline": "Press freedom is stifled in Guatemala ahead of an election", "subheadline": "No country for journalists", "seoPageTitle": null, "seoMetadataDescription": null, "ad": {"grapeshot": {"channels": null, "__typename": "Grapeshot"}, "__typename": "Ad"}, "audio": {"main": null, "__typename": "Media"}, "image": {"main": {"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/media-assets/image/20230624_AMP501.jpg", "__typename": "URL"}, "__typename": "Content", "height": 720, "width": 1280, "description": "Guatemalan journalist Jose Ruben Zamora is escorted by police for a court hearing"}, "promo": null, "__typename": "Media"}, "description": "Jos\u00e9 Rub\u00e9n Zamora, a graft-skewering editor, has been put behind bars", "datePublished": "2023-06-22T13:46:55Z", "dateModified": "2023-06-22T13:47:14Z", "dateRevised": "2023-06-22T13:46:55Z", "dateRevisedString": "Jun 22nd 2023", "datePublishedString": "Jun 22nd 2023", "dateCreated": "2023-06-21T10:50:00Z", "copyrightYear": 2023, "inLanguage": "en", "byline": "", "dateline": "Guatemala city", "text": [{"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"type": "tag", "name": "span", "attribs": {"data-caps": "initial"}, "children": [{"data": "J", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "small", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "os\u00e9 Rub\u00e9n Zamora", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": ", a Guatemalan journalist, has often exposed corruption in the Central American country. In 2008 he was kidnapped, beaten and drugged by unknown assailants, before being dumped outside the capital. Some 15 years later, he is still being targeted. On June 14th, a court sentenced Mr Zamora to six years in prison for money-laundering and ordered him to pay a $40,000 fine. He was cleared of charges of blackmail and influence-peddling. The case is widely considered spurious. It is a worrying sign of eroding press freedom ahead of the first round of a presidential election on June 25th.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "Alejandro Giammattei, the outgoing president (he cannot run again), insists the trial had nothing to do with journalism and everything to do with Mr Zamora\u2019s business activities, which included asking an acquaintance to deposit $40,000 in cash in a bank for him. Mr Zamora argues that the use of cash was necessary to protect donors from the ire of the authorities. ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "i", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "El Peri\u00f3dico", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": ", the newspaper Mr Zamora founded in 1996, closed in May\u2014he claims that the authorities repeatedly intimidated its donors and journalists (the government denies these allegations). ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "Mr Zamora\u2019s punishment is \u201ca very bad signal for democracy\u201d, says Carolina Jim\u00e9nez Sandoval, the head of the Washington Office on Latin America (", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "small", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "WOLA", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": "), an American think-tank. Ahead of this year\u2019s presidential election, the right to take part in politics has also been \u201cseverely violated\u201d, she notes. The country\u2019s electoral authorities have made apparently arbitrary decisions to bar candidates, including Carlos Pineda, a businessman who became the surprise front-runner after campaigning on TikTok, a video app.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "This is part of a broader trend of democratic backsliding. Several countries in Central America are moving in the direction of Daniel Ortega\u2019s Nicaragua, the original model for despotism in the region. The rule of law is quickly eroding in El Salvador under Nayib Bukele, its millennial president. Unlike these two other nations, though, Guatemala is not dominated by one individual. Rather, its political, military and economic elites entrench their hold on power through a system described by ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "small", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "WOLA", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": " as \u201ccorporate authoritarianism\u201d. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "Democracy started to unravel in Guatemala in 2019 when the then-president, Jimmy Morales, disbanded ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "small", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "CICIG", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": ", a ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "small", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "UN", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": "-created anti-impunity task-force. This trend deepened under his successor, Mr Giammattei. Threatened by questionable legal challenges, many lawyers and judges have fled the country in recent years. Since November two dozen journalists have gone into exile.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "When interviewed in May the founder of ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "i", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "El Peri\u00f3dico", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": " was handcuffed, well-dressed and gaunt after ten months in a cell. He correctly guessed that he would receive between five and seven years in jail, adding that Guatemalan democracy had always been imperfect, but that it had significantly worsened of late. \u201cWe are passing a threshold, and it will be progressively more difficult to practise journalism in Guatemala,\u201d he sighed. He believes the article that particularly irked the authorities before his arrest was a report on irregularities surrounding the government\u2019s covid-19 vaccine deal.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "tag", "name": "p", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "Marielos Monz\u00f3n, who is part of a media collective called ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "i", "attribs": {}, "children": [{"data": "NoNosCallar\u00e1n", "type": "text"}]}, {"data": " (They Will Not Silence Us), believes the sentencing of the \u201cemblematic\u201d Mr Zamora is a \u201cclear message\u201d to anyone who practises her profession. Ms Monz\u00f3n thinks the situation is the worst in the country since 1996, when the post-civil war era began. \u201cThey are leaving us two paths,\u201d she says. \u201cThe path to exile or the path to prison.\u201d ", "type": "text"}, {"type": "tag", "name": "span", "attribs": {"data-ornament": "ufinish"}, "children": [{"data": "\u25a0", "type": "text"}]}]}], "bodyText": "Jos\u00e9 Rub\u00e9n Zamora, a Guatemalan journalist, has often exposed corruption in the Central American country. In 2008 he was kidnapped, beaten and drugged by unknown assailants, before being dumped outside the capital. Some 15 years later, he is still being targeted. On June 14th, a court sentenced Mr Zamora to six years in prison for money-laundering and ordered him to pay a $40,000 fine. He was cleared of charges of blackmail and influence-peddling. The case is widely considered spurious. It is a worrying sign of eroding press freedom ahead of the first round of a presidential election on June 25th.\nAlejandro Giammattei, the outgoing president (he cannot run again), insists the trial had nothing to do with journalism and everything to do with Mr Zamora\u2019s business activities, which included asking an acquaintance to deposit $40,000 in cash in a bank for him. Mr Zamora argues that the use of cash was necessary to protect donors from the ire of the authorities. El Peri\u00f3dico, the newspaper Mr Zamora founded in 1996, closed in May\u2014he claims that the authorities repeatedly intimidated its donors and journalists (the government denies these allegations). \nMr Zamora\u2019s punishment is \u201ca very bad signal for democracy\u201d, says Carolina Jim\u00e9nez Sandoval, the head of the Washington Office on Latin America (WOLA), an American think-tank. Ahead of this year\u2019s presidential election, the right to take part in politics has also been \u201cseverely violated\u201d, she notes. The country\u2019s electoral authorities have made apparently arbitrary decisions to bar candidates, including Carlos Pineda, a businessman who became the surprise front-runner after campaigning on TikTok, a video app.\nThis is part of a broader trend of democratic backsliding. Several countries in Central America are moving in the direction of Daniel Ortega\u2019s Nicaragua, the original model for despotism in the region. The rule of law is quickly eroding in El Salvador under Nayib Bukele, its millennial president. Unlike these two other nations, though, Guatemala is not dominated by one individual. Rather, its political, military and economic elites entrench their hold on power through a system described by WOLA as \u201ccorporate authoritarianism\u201d. \nDemocracy started to unravel in Guatemala in 2019 when the then-president, Jimmy Morales, disbanded CICIG, a UN-created anti-impunity task-force. This trend deepened under his successor, Mr Giammattei. Threatened by questionable legal challenges, many lawyers and judges have fled the country in recent years. Since November two dozen journalists have gone into exile.\nWhen interviewed in May the founder of El Peri\u00f3dico was handcuffed, well-dressed and gaunt after ten months in a cell. He correctly guessed that he would receive between five and seven years in jail, adding that Guatemalan democracy had always been imperfect, but that it had significantly worsened of late. \u201cWe are passing a threshold, and it will be progressively more difficult to practise journalism in Guatemala,\u201d he sighed. He believes the article that particularly irked the authorities before his arrest was a report on irregularities surrounding the government\u2019s covid-19 vaccine deal.\nMarielos Monz\u00f3n, who is part of a media collective called NoNosCallar\u00e1n (They Will Not Silence Us), believes the sentencing of the \u201cemblematic\u201d Mr Zamora is a \u201cclear message\u201d to anyone who practises her profession. Ms Monz\u00f3n thinks the situation is the worst in the country since 1996, when the post-civil war era began. \u201cThey are leaving us two paths,\u201d she says. \u201cThe path to exile or the path to prison.\u201d \u25a0", "about": {"public": null, "__typename": "Taxonomies"}, "print": {"headline": "No country for journalists", "section": {"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/the-americas/", "__typename": "URL"}, "__typename": "Content", "headline": "The Americas"}, "__typename": "Print"}, "articleSection": {"public": null, "internal": [{"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/the-americas/", "__typename": "URL"}, "__typename": "Content", "id": "/content/u9avqma9ca3p14gs9dp3hjvt3ebg1mr5", "tegID": "u9avqma9ca3p14gs9dp3hjvt3ebg1mr5", "headline": "The Americas", "hasPart": {"parts": [{"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/the-americas/2023/06/22/annual-inflation-of-114-is-pushing-argentina-to-the-right", "__typename": "URL"}, "__typename": "Content", "id": "/content/uug0b52r5si56634n5u4r76qkqvrleci", "type": ["Article", "NewsArticle", "AnalysisNewsArticle"], "headline": "Annual inflation of 114% is pushing Argentina to the right", "subheadline": "It\u2019s still the economy, stupid", "datePublished": "2023-06-22T13:46:56Z", "description": "Patricia Bullrich and Javier Milei are rising in the polls for this year\u2019s presidential election", "image": {"main": {"url": {"canonical": "https://www.economist.com/media-assets/image/20230624_AMP001.jpg", "__typename": "UR